  "doc_id": "50351",
  "text": "Endothelial dysfunction and inflammation are believed to be involved in diseases such as atherosclerosis and diabetes (1, 2) . High concentrations of markers of inflammation and endothelial dysfunction, such as C-reactive protein (CRP), interleukin 6 (IL-6), E-selectin, and soluble intercellular adhesion molecule 1 (sICAM-1), have been shown to predict cardiovascular disease risk (3) (4) (5) . Data are also emerging about their involvement in the development of diabetes. A recent study showed a positive association between serum concentrations of sICAM-1 and E-selectin and risk of diabetes (6) . The associations between foods, nutrients, and these diseases may be mediated in part through inflammation and endothelial dysfunction. Studies have suggested a link between dietary intake of long-chain nҀ3 fatty acids and antioxidants and endothelial dysfunction [CITATION_1] and of alcohol [CITATION_2] , vitamin B-6 intake, and glycemic index [CITATION_3] and plasma CRP concentrations [CITATION_4] . However, data are scant on the association between overall dietary patterns and these biomarkers.",
